{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_anaconda_ver01/data/sn85053044/00517178135/1949022501/0060.xml":{"full_text":"THE BROWIHNG CHI\u00a3F\nJohn E. Davies, Editor and Owner\nA weekly newspaper published\nevery Friday at Browning, Glacier\nCounty, Montana.\nEntered as 2nd class matter July 15,\n1931 at the postoffice at Browning,\nMontana, under act of March 3, 1879.\nSubscription $2.00 year in advance\nliKwfiriwt i\u00dfsmct?\nThe break in commodity and\nstock markets, plus the laying\noff of worker in various indust\nries, is causing Americans to ask,\nIs this it?\nMore tensely than ever, busi\nness and government are tryng\nto guess whether the boom has\nended. More closely than ever\nthey are examining the bulwarks\nagainst a bust.\nThe majority of economists be\nlieve there will be a recession,\nnot a depression. A minority\nhold that many parts of the econ\nomy are still on the inflationary\nside. They support President\nTruman\u2019s view that controls and\ntaxes are needed. The majority\ndeclare there is now more need\nfor insurance against a slump,\nand would support Senator\nGeorge\u2019s view that new taxes\nshould wait at least until it is ap\nparent whether the economy is\ngoing up or down.\nHe is a wise man who can tell\nwhere political opinion leaves off\nand economic statistics begin.\nLabor leaders say living costs\nare still higher than a year ago\nand that employers are exagger\nating the decline in order to head\noff new wage demands. Busi\nnessmen say unions are inviting\nunemployment by renewed press\nure for higher wages and that\nnew taxes would promote hard\ntimes. A skeptical public may\nbe inclined to wonder whether\nthe economic experts can really\ntell what is going to happen bet\nter than the political experts\ncould before the election.\nAs impartial onlookers we are\nbound to record that the econo\nmists do have some pretty solid\nlooking guideposts. But some\ntimes we wonder whether they\ntake enough account of t h e in\ntangibles, the psychological fac\ntors. There appear to be many\nnew brakes available to keep the\nnational economy from plunging\nover the precipice of panic. But\npanic is so much a matter of\nwhat people fear rather than\nwhat the actual dangers are that\nno coldly statistical list of stabi\nlizing safeguards is wholly con\nvincing.\nAmong some of the factors the\neconomists believe will operate to\nprevent another 1929 crash are\nthe growing scarcity of raw\nmaterials, the improvement in in\nformation on economic develop\nments, farm price supports, the\nFriday to Friday Specials\nCrisco 3 lbs. $1.05\nSpam 12 oz. 49c\nOld Yellowstone No. 2 Can\nPork and beans 2 cans for 27c\nFisher\u2019s Cake Flour 2 lbs. 12c\nWhite King large 32c\nTable Queen Bread 4 loaves for 75c\nYOUNG FANCY BEEF\nPot Roast pound 39c\nBeef Ribs pound 29c\nHome Made Link Sausage\nOUR SPECIALTY\nFREE DELIVERY TWICE DAILY\n-Ji _\nf *viiiiii-ii\nsocial McuHty floor undier buying\npower, and the newly accepted\nresponsibility of government to\nprevent degressions. Certainly\nthe economy has greatly changed\nin the last 20 years, and these\ncushions against disastrous de\nflation afford hope fora much\nmore stable business level.\nBut do they provide sufficient\ninsurance? The chief reliance is\non government spending\u2014f o r\nprice supports, for social security,\nfor Marshall Plan operations, and\nfor new arms programs. In the\nlast resort there is also the pros\npect of huge public works to pro\nvide employment. But what hap\npens when the stored-up demand\nand buying power of wartime\nceases?\nHow long can the national ec\nonomy depend on export '\u2018hypo\ndermics\u201d like the Marshall Plan\nand the prospective program for\narming Atlantic Pact allies? Can\ngovernment really check a busi\nness landslide if private buyers\u2014\nfrom housewives to corporations\n\u2014all decide to wait for lower\nprice? If industry and,agriculture\ncut production instead of prices;\ndoesn't that pyramid the loss of\nproduction and employment\u2014and\nbuying power? If labor keeps its\nprices\u2014wages\u2014up/ won\u2019t less of\nit be bought?\nWhat happens if government\nspending is raised by $5,000,000,-\n000 but private spending falls off\nfour times that much? Are the\nblueprints ready for public works\nto make up that amount quickly?\nWould tax reductions stop a de\ncline? Would farm price supports\nhelp or hurt? Would labor take\nwage cuts and industry price cuts\nin order to promote consumption?\nIs the public prepared to approve\nheavy borrowing for federal\nspending in place of private buy\ning? Isn\u2019t there danger in forget\nting how large apa r t of pros-\nWe are now back at\nour best stride to\nserve you.\nDrop in and enjoy a\ngood, tastey meal.\nRegular meals and\nshort orders.\nFollick\nGrill\nWe Appreciate Your\nPatronage\nTHE BROWING CHIEF\nperity still depends on private\ninitiative? Isn\u2019t it clear that\ngovernment efforts must be\nprompt or they could fail to halt\na downward p 1u m g e and end\nmerely by palliating its effecfs?\n\u2014Christian Science Monitor.\nWashington Has\n\u201cHot\u201d Competition\nWashington\u2019s birthday ushered\nin a spell of more agreeable\nweather, the temperature rang\ning during the day from 35 to 50\nabove. Washington, it will be re\ncalled from history, crossed the\nDelaware in an open boat in a big\nstorm. His picture adorns Ameri\ncan currency and postage stamps.\nAlso, he was the first president\nof the United States. This sounds\nlike a \u201cthumbnail\u201d sketch clipped\nfrom a medicine almanac.\nFrankly, that appears to be the\ngrowing reaction of this illustri\nous American these days, wh o\nhas little chance of being greatly\nremembered when there a r e so\nmany \u201chot\u201d lesser lights compet\ning.\nAnnouncement\nBrowning Laundry\nIs Now Operating\nin Quarters West\nof Buttreys Food\nStore, under the\nManagement of\nMrs. Sinnett.\n[Bi THE DARING NEW DODGE\nBUILT FOR TODAY'S BIGGER, TALLER, MORE ACTIVE A